The '''Semelidae'''  are a [[family (biology)|family]] of saltwater [[clam]]s, [[Marine (ocean)|marine]] [[bivalve]] [[mollusc]]s in the order [[Veneroida]], the venus shells and their allies.

==Description==
Menbers of this family have rounded or oval, elongated shells, much flattened. The two valves are connected by an internal ligament in contrast to the closely related family [[Tellinidae]] where the ligament is external. The two separate siphons are very long, sometimes several times the length of the shell. These siphons have a characteristic cruciform muscle at their base.<ref>Barrett, J. H. and C. M. Yonge, 1958. Collins Pocket Guide to the Sea Shore. P. 160. Collins, London</ref>

